<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-928-646  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 928 646.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX Review  Nov 1989 v7 n11 p122(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Miller Freeman Publications 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fast but cheap. (Hewlett-Packard Co.'s Apollo Series 2500workstation)(Recent Releases) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hewlett-Packard Co. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    HWP.andO;Product:   HP Apollo 2500 (Workstation) (product introduction).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Fast But CheapandM;It is clear even to the uninitiated that the focus of the new line ofworkstations introduced by Hewlett-Packard Co. through its Apollo division ison the low end.andP;  The Apollo Series 2500 personal workstation, priced from$3990, is based on a 20 MHz Motorola 68030 microprocessor with a MC68882coprocessor, and features high-resolution graphics.andP;  Up to seven 200 MB3-1/2-inch SCSI devices can be attached.andP;  The machine can further accommodate2.3 GB of mass storage, a floppy disk, and a tape drive.andP;  It comes with 4 MBto 16 MB of main memory and a choice of 15-inch or 19-inch monochromemonitor.andM;HP claims that two other workstation lines it introduced, the Series 3500 andSeries 4500 desktop visualization systems, can draw up to 20,000 3Dsmooth-shaded polygons and 300,000 3D vectors per second.andP;  They are based onthe 25 MHz and 33 MHz 68030.andP;  The systems are available in 40- andeight-plane versions, and can be tailored to applications such as solidsmodeling, fluid dynamics, image processing, mapping, and 3D wireframe design.andO;A dedicated drawing engine and transformation processor accelerate theredrawing of wireframe images and solids models and speed upfloating-point-intensive operations.andP;  graphics tasks are offloaded from theCPU to the dedicated transformation processor.andP;  Also featured aredouble-buffering, the ability to specify multiple light sources, and a Zbuffer.andP;  Both machines are offered with a 19-inch color monitor and 4 MB to32 MB of main memory, and both support up to 2.8 GB of local mass storage.andO;Prices for eight-plane versions of the workstations begin at $19,495, and for40-plane versions at $27,495.andM;All three systems utilize the Domain/OS operating system, which combinesSystem V with Berkeley extensions and Apollo's Aegis.andM;HP, Palo Alto, CA.andP;  508-256-6600.andO;</TEXT></DOC>